public class java_44150_CredentialValidator_A01 {    // start with 'class' keyword followed by the classname. In Java, classes should begin with a capital letter to be recognized while accessing them using objects of that particular type in java program later on . So starting from here will follow standard OOP practices and best practice too!
   public boolean validate(String userName, String password) { // method definition starts following this line. 'public' keyword denotes it can access outside the class only if there are no errors till then - we need not worry about that in real world scenarios as per Java standards!! Also a single space between name and opening bracket is preferred here for readability (java coding conventions).
        boolean valid = false; // local variable initialization starts following this line. We're assuming if the userName equals 'admin' AND password equal to 1234, then it should be considered as a successful login by default! In real world scenarios you need much more complex logic for handling multiple users and their corresponding credentials which would complicate things further in code but will provide comprehensive understanding of validation.
        if (userName != null && userName.equals("admin")  // If condition to check username is not empty AND equals 'Admin' -> Then true, else false; In real world scenarios also we need a more complex logic for checking password and comparing it with stored hash value from database or somewhere in the realm of actual application!
                && (password != null && password.equals("1234"))) {  // If condition to check userName is not NULL AND equals 'admin' as well AS also PASSWORD IS NOT empty, THEN true else false; Here again we need a more complex logic for handling multiple users and their corresponding credentials which will complicate things further in code but provide comprehensive understanding of validation.
            valid = true; // If both conditions are met then set the boolean value to 'true' so as you have successfully authenticated user! In real world scenarios, passwords should be stored hashed for security reasons instead or something like this and we need a more complex logic in that case too but again due complexity it will provide comprehensive understanding of validation.
        } // end if condition check whether the entered username is 'admin' AND corresponding passed word(password) are both not empty then valid should be set to true otherwise false as per requirements!  In real world applications, also this logic needs handle and much more scenarios for handling user inputs etc... but due complexity it will provide comprehensive understanding of validation.
        return valid; // This method returns a boolean which is the output result by evaluating if entered username equals 'admin' AND password corresponds to some value (and as per requirements) then returning true else false, In real world applications also this logic needs handle and much more scenarios for handling user inputs etc... but again due complexity it will provide comprehensive understanding of validation.
    } // End method definition after the semicolon at end followed by closing bracket '}' which indicates termination to Java compiler that a statement is complete (end)!  So, remember in real world scenario also handle and consider all scenarios for handling user inputs etc... but due complexity it will provide comprehensive understanding of validation.
} // End class definition after the semicolon at end followed by closing bracket '}' which indicates termination to Java compiler that a statement is complete (end)! So, remember in real world scenario also handle and consider all scenarios for handling user inputs etc... but due complexity it will provide comprehensive understanding of validation.